segments.text: September 27, in the lobby of the Kleberg Center, getting ready to interview Dean of Agriculture, Emeritus Harry Kunkel.
Harry, test your mic.

Harry, to introduce a future reader of the transcription or listener to the tape, to introduce them to you, would you describe your growing up years and your experience before you came to A&M to enroll as a student?
Where did you grow up and what did you do and what was your family doing and so forth?
I grew up about four miles outside of the city of Alney.
just across the county line in Archer County, Texas.
It was a farm, a 252 acre farm.
The family did own another 1100 and some acres near Westover, Texas.
I was one of two children.
My brother was some nine years younger than me, and therefore I was in school and away, essentially older than he at the time that he came along.
I did not start school until I was seven years old.
And the school that I went to was a church school, a private school, approximately one and a half miles away from our home.
It was a Lutheran school.
And I went into that Lutheran school all the way through the eighth grade, which then was the first year of high school.
Did you, was the instruction in English or German?
The instruction was in English.
but there were of course German reading exercises and the like.
It was not as much bilingual as one might have thought.
My home was probably more bilingual.
My grandfather and grandmother lived with us during the early period of life.
I was probably a pretty shy kind of a person at that point in time.

although I found that I was able to, I guess, get along with the grades all right, because I went through the first grade with a beloved teacher, Miss Johanna Schwaus, and don't ask me how the bad friend spelled her name.
Then other teachers came.
These were male teachers that were usually in Divinity School and stepped out a year in order to teach as sort of an internship type of activity.
What were the money crops on the Kunkel farm?
The money crops on the Kunkel farm were basically wheat,
There was no cotton particularly.
The cotton picking apparently went by the wayside early in my life because of the labor and things of the sort.
It was principally wheat and hay and cattle.
The money crops, of course, were butter and eggs and some chickens.
And when you all went to town, it was to Olney?
When we went to town, it was to Olney.
We generally went on Saturdays because Saturday was the afternoon and everybody came into Saturday.
That's when I went into the Tencent movie, usually in the afternoon while folks sat out.
On the evenings, the people would park along the main street and watch the people as they moved back and forth and made friends and this kind of a thing.
Sunday was probably the biggest social activity that we went to.
Oftentimes we would end up being invited on the spur of the moment to somebody's home and having dinner.
That's the Sunday meal.
And then would you go back to church after that long dinner, or did you go home then?
We went home after that.
Was there a Sunday evening service?
Sometimes there was a Sunday evening service, and we would go to that.
This was Missouri Synod Lutheran?
This was Missouri Synod Lutheran.
So conservative in its theology?
Conservative, very conservative in its theology.
How long had your family lived out there?
My family moved back there before, I'm not quite sure how long.
It was before the 1900s.
They lived at this place.
They bought it in the latter part of the 19th century.
Right, and at Olney High School, how many were in your graduating class?
Do you remember?
There were about 80 in my graduating class, 83 in the graduating class.
Let me tell you about my work.
I went all the way through high school, and my first year of high school, I still stayed out at this private school.
I was the only one in class.
And of course, it had to be a tutorial type of activity up to that particular point.
I went only to high school for two and a half years.
I transferred my grades without any difficulty.
I started moving ahead, taking courses, and had no particular problems.
But along the way, we had become members of a 4-H club, and that 4-H club
I had calves and whatever, chickens and a few other things.
It was a 4-H club that perhaps was more of a creative or more of an effect, had an effect on my life and my future than anything else because the church had no particular effect.
I had wanted to be a minister when I was young, but I decided something earlier wouldn't be there.
It was in the 4-H club situations and I began to show calves.
I grew a crop of grain sorghum which was new and it was on judging teams the first year.
I was 14 years old, or 13 years old.
I was 14 years old.
I was on the county meat identification camp.
We came here for the 4-H round of Farmers Roundup at that particular point in time.
So your first visit to College Station?
Was in association with 4-H work.
And about your first year at Olney?
High school?
About the first year at Alney High School.
What year would that be then, if you were 14?
That would have been 1937.
Do you remember your impression of A&M at that time?
My impression of A&M was a very solid impression, and probably that was the reason why I said I was going to come here and be a student here.
At any rate,
team from our county, one state, and then we were invited to the Chicago, to the National 4-H Conference.
Oh my goodness.
And did our judging there, and we were somewhere down the line, about seventh or eighth in among the states.
I went next year and decided I couldn't go back in this, so I went to the poultry judging team, and one state.

and went to Chicago once again on a judging team, and made a considerable number of friends, particularly at that point in time, who turned out to be friends and people who I knew at Texas A&M University.
Who were some of those A&M?
Oh, names fail me.
These were faculty?
No.
Oh, students.
Oh, I see, I see.
They were students.
In your family, was there any particular time when you can recall it was decided you were going to go to college?
Or had your parents had that?
I don't really know whether it was a particular time.
I think I grew up with the idea that I was going to college no matter what.
That was expected of me at the very outset.
But your parents had not.
No, my parents' mother went through four years of school, and of course learned to read in a private school.
My dad went to public school, and then he later on, he came to Blinn College down in Brenham,
and did some high school work at Blinn.
All right.
When did you begin to make formal contact with A&M about application and what was the process where you applied and were admitted?
Do you remember?
You got a catalog and you got the application blank and you sent it in and somewhere before September 1939,
You didn't come for any kind of summer orientation or anything like that?
No, there was no such thing as a summer orientation.
The only thing is that I knew the campus somewhat in the summer of 1939.
They had changed the format of the program and they asked several of us to chair certain programs.
No, these were programs, presentations at the 4-H Roundup, you see, or at the Farmer's Roundup, Farmer's Roundup as it was called.
And at the 4-H, it's 4-H Roundup now, it was 4-H with the Farmer's Roundup at that point.
That was probably my first contact with anyone of any real consequence.
at Texas A&M University because I was chairing a program put on by the College of Engineering.
And so I went to see and visit Mr. Gilchrist.
I became acquainted with him, and he was actually the first person.
It's interesting that the first person I knew was the dean of engineering rather than the... Can you describe your impression of him?
Well, I was impressed.
Obviously, he was the dean.
I was not taken back by him because he had a very outgoing personality at that point in time.
Describe him physically.
What did he look like?
He seemed to be a large man.
That's about all I can remember of him.
But was pleasant with a student, a prospective student?
He was pleasant with me.
I can't say anything else.
Now, on these visits to A&M, before you came to enroll, you came on the train or how?
Automobile.
Oh, an automobile.
Okay.
About how long did it take then to drive from Alneta?
I would say, oh, on the order of eight hours or something like that.
So a long day.
It was a long day, yeah.
All right.
Now, when you came as a student, you're coming to enroll, how did you come?
Who brought you?
What did you bring?
My parents brought me.
And then left me.
Left me at my quarters at that particular point in time.
What kind of vehicle did you all have then?
We had Chevrolets.
We bought a Chevrolet either every year or every other year.
So y'all...
The cost was, oh, on the order of $400 a year.
But y'all were doing better than most Texas farmers then.
We had some oil.
Oh really?
We had some oil and this is probably what allowed us to have such things as during the early period of time we built a new house during my years, a rock house.
We had electricity by a 32-volt generator with a set of batteries.
You always have to buy the 32-volt appliances.
They weren't always available.
Did you have a telephone on the farm?
We did not have a telephone.
How near was it to a telephone?
Okay, you went to town.
What did you, if you can, describe what you brought with you when you came to enroll?
What belongings did you bring?

I suspect I brought, I recall I brought a minimum amount of belongings because we were all going to be in uniform and there was a certain amount of uniform that was issued and then I went back to Waldrop's over here at the North Gate.
I met Mr. Waldrop and he took me in and mother said that if he needs anything I give it to him.
We'll pay for it, help him out.
And essentially bought the uniform and it was that.
There was a few things like a sweater.
We were kind of raunchy looking for cool work at that point.
And where did you live that first year?
I lived in Russell Hall.
Russell Hall.
It's a project house.
Oh, okay.
The very first project house that was built.
It's off campus, as a matter of fact.
Where was it located?
It's on the south gate over here, just off, I don't recall the street.
I recall where...
Following that period of time, there were some drugstore being built and things of the sort.
How long had it been a project house?
I really don't know.
It was certainly there.
Now, after that, using that as a pattern, they had built quite a series, quite a series of project houses on campus.
And those were already, were they already there at that time?
But yours was the first one.
That was the first one.
Describe the routine of the house.
How many were there?
There were, I'd say, about 20 students.
This was Washington County.
And how did you qualify?
Well, I had lots of relatives in Redham.
I knew some people that knew some people
apparently was able to make application and be accepted by the Washington County group.
And so most of them were Washington County boys.
Most of them were Washington County.
There were three or four others or five others that were not.
And all of you were in the Corps.
All of us were in the Corps.
As a matter of fact, Corps life...
extended out to the project houses in a way, in an incomplete way, and I'll tell you why I say that in a minute.
The project house was essentially handled by a lady who had been selected who was a
And she had some people to help with keeping the house, but we, of course, had to clean our rooms.
We had inspections by the military.
We were hazed.
Were the hazers from within the house?
They were within the house, yes.
We had paddles and other things that were good.
We were able to stand it.
There wasn't particularly any protection.
Did you all fall out on the grass outside the house?
No, it was all on the second floor.
Oh, okay.
In the hallways.
As far as you know, the house had been built by Washington County people and or money?
It was either built or bought by Washington County.
Describe your room, who was in it, and what was in it.
Well, I had two roommates, one of which had come down with me by the name of Cole.
He didn't blast very long.
He left.
He dropped out of A&M and went to Columbia, Texas Tech.
I was a little disappointed in it.
And I had another roommate by the name of Harry K. Lisser from Chapel Hill.
And I think we became friends.
He's now passed on.
Were most of these youngsters Germanic in their ancestry?
No.
No.
No, as a matter of fact, most of them were not.
The Germanic people, I think, in Washington County and most of them, really, my family was over in Austin County.
And they were not, at that point in time, college goers.
I see.
I see.
So you found that most of that, I'd say the group, they had names like Alsabrook and so on.
All right.
And the lady who kind of ran the house, how did she come, who selected her?
Well, that was something that was done in association.
Obviously, there had been people that were sort of sponsoring the project house and people associated with the project house.
And she was selected.
She was a native of Chapel Hill, which is in Washington.
And of course, it was closed during the summertime.
Suddenly, during the regular section, the project house was open.
Did she, was she the kind of master sergeant of things in terms of making?
Not really, no.
She was more of a...
person that you could talk to, listen to, but generally she was just a mother.
And did she do the cooking?
She did the cooking.
Did y'all all, describe the meal routine.
The meal routine is that we all came down at a meal and had it for breakfast and lunch and evening meal.
I guess we called it supper.
And they were all full meals, family style?
Family style meals, yeah.
What were some of the foods that you remember that were particularly good?
I am not sure I remember any that were particularly good at all.
Was it similar to what you remember at home?
I remember at home fried chicken and occasionally fried steak, thin battered round steak that had been beaten and battered.
Now, did you and your fellow residents of that house, did you all pay cash or did you pay partly in kind?
I think, well, we paid cash.
I paid cash at least.
Do you remember what the cost was?
It was on the order of $23 a month.
Okay.
Who did the washing?
We didn't do washing there.
We took our clothes to the laundry.
Okay.
We took our clothes to the laundry.
All right.
When did you and your fellow residents participate in the routine of the entire campus in terms of core activities and so forth?
Well, there was a drill once a week.
And that's when we joined the organization in which we were assigned to.
I was assigned to Sea Battery Field Artillery, a horse-drawn unit.
I was a member of that organization.
I was never hazed by them, but I was a member of that organization.
And I met them on one day a week.
Did it have a nickname, that outfit?
The nicknames seem to have arrived in the 50s.
Were you all ever teased about kind of being outside the real core activity?
Were you fully accepted?
I don't recall that we were teased.
We were not.
I don't know that we were also fully accepted.
What can you do?
We were meeting, and you had assignments and things of a sort.
Once a week, two hours at best.
You did meet, you did know some of the students, but you knew some of your fellow freshmen.
And, of course, you knew the CO and the first sergeant.
But you had students at that house from all four grades.
All four levels, freshmen, sophomores, juniors, seniors.
And you wore your uniforms just like everyone else.
We wore our uniforms just like everybody else.
We had the same requirements of wearing the uniforms that everybody did.
Describe as well as you can a typical class day, Monday through Friday.
Now, I know you had half-day classes on Saturday, but let's do a full day.
What time did you get up, and what happened when?
Well, we got up, I guess, about 6 o'clock or 6.30.
I don't recall.
At least I was able to get up.
There was a call in the house to get everybody up for breakfast.
And then we went.
If we didn't have anything to do, we were
other than clean up our room, that's what we did.
Otherwise we went to the rooms and studied.
There was no real area at that particular point in that project house where you have a common place.
And then you took off and walked to class.
And whatever class that you have, it took 18 hours or
So that meant essentially six classes, six different courses that you were taking.
Then in the afternoons, when you didn't have any classes, where did you?
Well, we had classes in the afternoon because we had laboratories.
Out of a lot of the classes that we had, we had laboratory classes.
At that time, the School of Agriculture courses, curricula,
were agriculture curriculum.
And the first year, essentially, you went through a round robin situation.
You took a course in agronomy, you took a course in agricultural economics, which turned out to be geography, agricultural geography.
You took a course in animal science, husbandry.
You took a course in ag engineering.
You took all in poultry science.
I guess I didn't take one in poultry, but I did take one in dairy.
So all ag majors were introduced to a fairly broad scope.
And there was no such thing as credit by examination or anything like that then, was there?
Where you could get some, I'd never heard of it.
The only thing that you had, if you made a certain amount of grades level, you were exempt from the final exam.
Mm-hmm.
And if you had any spare time when you didn't have a class or a lab, where did you spend that time?
In the library.
I'm smiling because I've heard that from a number, and I've heard that a few sometimes found a quiet corner where they might be able to take a nap.
Well, I didn't do that.
I found...
the music room.
Now this is Cushing Library.
Cushing Library.
I found the music room and checked out the records.
And I don't know how many times I listened to Aida.
Now I assume at the project house that there wasn't much loud radio
played at night because there would be others studying.
Now, back to the house physically.
If there were 20 young men there, describe the toilet and shower facilities in that project house.
There was a toilet and shower facility on each floor.
Okay.
About how many could shower at the same time in one of those?
But it wasn't a single shower.
It wasn't a single shower.
Did you all play...
It was a community shower.
But you farm boys were not intimidated by that, I'm assuming.
No, it was a community shower.
We went in.
Were most of your fellow residents boys from the country?
No, some were from Brenham, if you call that country.
No.
Chapel Hill.
Okay.
I was as much from the country as anybody, I guess.
Okay.
Were there any rituals at mealtime about the way the food was passed around or who ate first?
You had a usual freshman type of ritual, but you had to pass it on.
Of course, the language that was there
It came from the campus?
It came from the campus.
I've heard a number of stories that sometimes young freshmen went home at Thanksgiving or Christmas and forgot and used some of their slang and made their mothers.
Did that happen to you?
I don't think so.
I at least don't recall any horror along that particular line.
In terms of family relations, about how often did you write a letter home and or get a letter back from home?
I guess two or three times a week.
And do you remember your mother sending you any cookies or candy?
No, she came to visit me one time and...
That freshman year?
That freshman year, in the fall.
And then they came and picked me up.
We had friends, people living in Holly, who were in school here, and I knew them, and I used to ride home, ride back, and occasionally just plain old hitchhiking.
Describe Aggie hitchhiking as you remember it.
Well, the point at which hitchhiking started essentially was downtown Bryan.
and or out in front of the gate going.
This, there was everybody had a particular place and when you came there you set your bag in order and you sort of sat and waited till somebody, somebody did the thumbing
when you finally got down to you or somebody going to some place you wanted to where they wanted, there was a special reason that you could jump the crowd.
You did it, but you didn't do it on it.
It was strictly with... Class rank and core rank had no...
They had no time to do it.
It was when you arrived.
Did you ever have any negative hitchhiking experience on somebody gave you a ride that
